",\n    \"author\": \"Svanik Kolli\",\n    \"total_votes\": 94,\n    \"last_run_time\": \"2026-05-21T00:10:38.070000Z\",\n    \"is_private\": false,\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:00:35.469889Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"ref\": \"romantamrazov/rogii-better-solution-lb-9-956\",\n    \"title\": \"[ROGII] BETTER SOLUTION | LB: 9.956\",\n    \"author\": \"Roman Tamrazov\",\n    \"total_votes\": 92,\n    \"last_run_time\": \"2026-05-10T10:12:21.040000Z\",\n    \"is_private\": false,\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:00:35.758850Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"ref\": \"yaroslavkholmirzayev/rogii-sel15-forced-selector\",\n    \"title\": \"ROGII SEL15 Forced Selector\",\n    \"author\": \"Yaroslav kholmirzayev\",\n    \"total_votes\": 86,\n    \"last_run_time\": \"2026-06-12T15:34:26.873000Z\",\n    \"is_private\": false,\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:00:37.913824Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"ref\": \"lightningv08/lb-7-776-rogii-ridge-sp\",\n    \"title\": \"[LB 7.776]rogii-ridge-sp\",\n    \"author\": \"Vladislav Lavrentev\",\n    \"total_votes\": 85,\n    \"last_run_time\": \"2026-06-07T16:28:33.390000Z\",\n    \"is_private\": false,\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:00:35.758872Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"ref\": \"aiwody/physical-model-less-overfitting-noise\",\n    \"title\": \"Physical model - less overfitting noise\",\n    \"author\": \"\\u8424\\u706b2018\",\n    \"total_votes\": 78,\n    \"last_run_time\": \"2026-06-04T01:30:54.907000Z\",\n    \"is_private\": false,\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:00:35.758884Z\"\n\n---discussions file---\n[\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 697418,\n    \"title\": \"Diagram of the problem\",\n    \"author\": \"Zacchaeus\",\n    \"author_username\": \"zacchaeus\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"MASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 127,\n    \"comment_count\": 9,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F4080021%2F3f56527c733365a94d929bdc0600c7ef%2Fig_023b4ba06ac0441e0169fa9248ca54819aacb93888a02601a8.png?generation=1778029361497538&alt=media)\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697418\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-06T01:02:47.450389300Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-06-09T21:01:13.203333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371548Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 698825,\n    \"title\": \"How Geologists Interpret Wells: Some Helpful Tips\",\n    \"author\": \"Igor Kuvaev\",\n    \"author_username\": \"igorakuvaev\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 51,\n    \"comment_count\": 3,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"Kagglers, \\nyou are doing great so far, and we are excited to see the improving RMSE on the leaderboard.\\nIn the comments on this post, I will share some helpful tricks that geologists use to come up with the best interpretations.\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/698825\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-11T18:36:29.863271400Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-11T19:36:50.590Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371601Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 697406,\n    \"title\": \"Geological Formations on well Geology (region: Texas)\",\n    \"author\": \"Mar\\u00edlia Prata\",\n    \"author_username\": \"mpwolke\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 49,\n    \"comment_count\": 2,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"## Geological Formations\\n\\nANCC, ASTNU, ASTNL, EGFDU, EGFDL, BUDA - Predicted depth of various geological formations (Training only). And Categorical labels indicating the geological unit in Geology column (train typewells)\\n\\n### BUDA Limestone\\n\\n\\\"The Buda Limestone is a dense white to yellow sparry limestone with numerous calcite veins that weathers to yellowish or pinkish due to its iron content.\\\"\\n\\nCoordinates\\t30.0849\\u00b0N 97.8507\\u00b0W - Region: North America\\n\\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buda_Limestone\\n\\n### ANCC - Anacacho Limestone\\n\\n\\\"The Anacacho Limestone is a unit of limestone of Cretaceous (Campanian) age in Texas. Most of the Anacacho Limestone is interpreted as having accumulated in relatively shallow (<50 m depth) marine water.\\\"\\n\\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anacacho_Limestone\\n\\n\\n### ASTNU and ASTNL \\n\\nAustin Chalk (U = **Upper Austin Chalk**, L = **Lower Austin Chalk**).\\n\\n\\\"The Austin Chalk is an upper Cretaceous geologic formation in the Gulf Coast region of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The rocks of the Austin Chalk consist of recrystallized, fossiliferous, interbedded chalks and marls. Exposures of Austin Chalk are mainly seen in quarries, roadcuts, and stream beds where water eroded the soil. \\\"\\n\\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austin_Chalk\\n\\n### EFGDU and EFGDL  \\n\\nEagle Ford (U = **Upper Eagle Ford**, L = **Lower Eagle Ford**).\\n\\n\\\"The **Eagle Ford Group** (also called the Eagle Ford Shale) is a sedimentary rock formation deposited during the Cenomanian and Turonian ages of the Late Cretaceous over much of the modern-day state of Texas. The Eagle Ford is predominantly composed of organic matter-rich fossiliferous marine shales and marls with interbedded thin limestones.\\\"\\n\\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_Ford_Group\\n\\n### Olmos\\n\\n\\\"The Olmos Formation is a Late Cretaceous formation in the easternmost portion of the Rio Grande Embayment of the Gulf Coast Basin in Texas. It is the uppermost unit in the Campanian Taylor Group of Texas, unconformably overlain by the Escondido Formation and underlain by San Miguel Formation . Both of the Escondido and San Miguel Formations are sequences of mudstone and sandstone.\\\"\\n\\nhttps://gccc.beg.utexas.edu/co2-data/olmos-00\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697406\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-05T23:00:26.955260900Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-15T02:18:26.703333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371613Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 699853,\n    \"title\": \"multi-trajectory prediction (MTP) with deep CNN for welllog inversion\",\n    \"author\": \"hengck23\",\n    \"author_username\": \"hengck23\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 47,\n    \"comment_count\": 92,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"example notebook\\nhttps://www.kaggle.com/code/hengck23/cnn-mtp-example?scriptVersionId=320093395\\n\\narvix paper: \\\"Direct Multi-Modal Inversion of Geophysical Logs Using Deep Learning\\\" - Sergey Alyaev  \\nhttps://arxiv.org/pdf/2201.01871\\nhttps://nfes.org/assets/workshop2022/ambrus_sequential_multi_mode_inversion_poster.pdf\\n\\n```\\n[2D Heatmap Input] \\u2500\\u2500> [Regression Head (CNN)] \\u2500\\u2500> [MDN Predictor (MLP)] \\u2500\\u2500> [Multi-Trajectory Output]\\n\\nexample of heatmap is shown below.\\nThe Mixture Density Network (MDN) Predictor : for multiple paths hypothesis (like k-beam).\\n\\nif you can identify match keypoints in GR signals, then you decide how to move/traverse between the matched keypoints.\\n```\\n\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2F7482e84e8978ff732cdcc907d6f9d684%2FSelection_3550.png?generation=1778852910817071&alt=media)\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2F6c2c44a7ecf5436b444bd418ea7b96bb%2FSelection_3551.png?generation=1778852946405152&alt=media)\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2F2d908d758ec3e6c9b53ef3ea87db67f4%2FSelection_3552.png?generation=1778852956595369&alt=media)\\n\\n\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/699853\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-15T13:49:18.283461700Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-06-08T10:14:32.910Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371623Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 700424,\n    \"title\": \"Share an UI visualizer \",\n    \"author\": \"Tom\",\n    \"author_username\": \"tom99763\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"MASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 46,\n    \"comment_count\": 60,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F4310004%2F8fe8f43532b152aa5a7637b7d6f1a2fe%2FUI1.png?generation=1779022020724846&alt=media)\\n\\nFeel free to use it: https://github.com/tom99763/rogii-viewer  \\n\\nAnd some EDA & directions in attachments. I suggest people to read `glossary.html` first to clarify some confused definition. \\n\\nI really like this explaination about TVT:\\n\\n```\\nAnalogy: TVT is the \\u201cfloor number\\u201d in a geological building\\n\\nImagine the geology as a completed high-rise building, where each floor represents a different rock layer (ANCC, Austin Chalk, Eagle Ford, Buda, etc.).\\n\\nTypewell = the elevator shaft: it goes vertically from the top floor to the basement, recording \\u201cthe GR at this layer is X\\u201d as it passes through each floor.\\nHorizontal well = a person walking inside the building:  moving along the hallway of a certain floor, sometimes going up or down between floors.\\nTVT = which floor is this person currently on?\\n```\\n\\n### Update GR Mismatch Visualizer\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F4310004%2F5b91ffbfc5d669a76d10fe1cb409dcb5%2FGR.png?generation=1779030611267623&alt=media)\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/700424\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-17T12:47:20.845780400Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-06-13T03:26:44.953333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371638Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 697431,\n    \"title\": \"besides regression, also dwt (time warping)! \",\n    \"author\": \"hengck23\",\n    \"author_username\": \"hengck23\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 34,\n    \"comment_count\": 36,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"related to geosteering. Here, given a strip of MD-GR of the horizontal well, \\\"stretch and fold\\\" it so that it matches the TVT-GR reference of the typewell\\n\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2Fb40517687f05f7ecea819763d3b150dc%2FSelection_3412.png?generation=1778261192499811&alt=media)\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2F6f36c16fad39781039af137e753996dd%2FSelection_3304.png?generation=1778038684983121&alt=media)\\n\\n\\n---\\n\\nbut, since the test and train locations are pretty close, pure regression might just also work\\n\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697431\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-06T03:38:07.141461Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-26T15:42:49.200Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371648Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 697416,\n    \"title\": \"Welcome to ROGII - Wellbore Geology Prediction!\",\n    \"author\": \"Igor Kuvaev\",\n    \"author_username\": \"igorakuvaev\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 28,\n    \"comment_count\": 14,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"We (ROGII) are excited to welcome you to this challenge.\\n\\nThe presented dataset is a very typical example of modern horizontal drilling data. It contains the well trajectory along with Gamma Ray (GR) measurements collected along the wellbore. This dataset can be confidently interpreted by an experienced human interpreter.\\n\\nWe look forward to the results of this competition, as they may help enable automation during the well drilling process.\\n\\nWe strongly encourage you to **review the PowerPoint presentation attached to the competition data**, as it contains key information on horizontal well interpretation.\\n\\nAdditionally, feel free to watch how the manual geosteering process works:\\nhttps://youtu.be/VgzFt7xknGo?si=LfqTlmjsZpNmtbJH&t=1034\\n\\nMost importantly, make sure you enjoy the competition. You are solving a real-world problem, and successful solutions will be greatly appreciated by the industry by making drilling safer, more efficient, and lower in emissions.\\n\\nIf you have any questions, we would be happy to address them.\\n\\n\\u2014 On behalf of all organizers,\\nROGII\\n\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697416\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-06T00:04:21.663312300Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-06-09T21:57:50.866666700Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371657Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 699289,\n    \"title\": \"Paradigm Shift: Why pure Tabular Models might be hitting a wall (Spatial & Sequential Context)\",\n    \"author\": \"Amged Alfaqih\",\n    \"author_username\": \"AmgedAlfaqih\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 21,\n    \"comment_count\": 4,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"**Hi everyone,**\\n\\nAfter spending some time diving deep into the data and experimenting with various preprocessing pipelines, I noticed a common trap we might all be falling into: treating this purely as a standard tabular regression problem.\\n\\nIf you are just passing [X, Y, Z, MD, GR] into LightGBM or XGBoost, you will eventually hit a hard ceiling on your CV/LB score. Why? Because the models are missing the physical and spatial realities of the wellbore trajectory.\\n\\n## **1. The Sequential Reality (Physics of the Drill)**\\n\\nWe aren't just looking at random rows; we are tracing a path. Features like MD (Measured Depth) and Z dictate a trajectory.\\n\\nInstead of simple lags and rolling windows, has anyone experimented with Particle Filters (PF) or Beam Search? By treating the expected TVT as a moving particle that updates its state based on the Gamma Ray (GR) observations and spatial constraints, we can create incredibly strong baseline predictions to feed into our Gradient Boosting models.\\n\\n## **2. The Spatial Reality (Geology is Continuous)**\\n\\nA well doesn't exist in a vacuum; it shares the same geological formation as its neighbors.\\n\\nRelying solely on X and Y coordinates in a tree model is inefficient. A better approach is using Spatial Imputation (like cKDTree) to find the nearest known wells and calculate the median TVT or formation depth in that specific localized area.\\n\\nFeeding this \\\"spatial neighborhood consensus\\\" as a feature massively stabilizes the predictions for unseen evaluation rows.\\n\\nBy shifting the focus from \\\"tuning model hyperparameters\\\" to \\\"building physics-aware and spatial-aware features\\\", the performance jump is massive.\\n\\nAre you guys currently using any sequential tracking (like Particle Filters/Kalman Filters) or mostly relying on heavy rolling/lag statistical features?\\n\\nWould love to hear your thoughts!\\n\\n\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/699289\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-13T12:22:48.528355700Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-16T18:59:08.736666700Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371666Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 698449,\n    \"title\": \"Duplicate type wells for different horizontal wells\",\n    \"author\": \"RMorrison\",\n    \"author_username\": \"rmorrison0\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 19,\n    \"comment_count\": 3,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"When doing a quick EDA, I noticed there are a few type well files that are exactly the same but assigned to different horizontal wells. In some cases this makes sense (wells that are oriented adjacent or on top of each other), but in other cases the wells are quite distant from each other. Why would wells some distance apart be using exactly the same type well? Is this intentional?\\n\\nHere are the well pairs with matching type wells, and a picture of how they are oriented compared to other wells with different type wells.\\n\\nduplicate_groups = [\\n    ['02e7fe5a', '10b89021', '3417285d', '6ae68655', '7993a768', 'bc4381e2', 'ecdab904', 'f021b650', 'f49fdea3', 'f88ddb26'],\\n    ['071d7b45', '4463446c'],\\n    ['25939962', '8050c789'],\\n    ['2f8e53c3', '91db7070'],\\n    ['75cd5f11', 'be83e781'],\\n    ['7b38844c', 'ed6e6e54'],\\n    ['89f1085d', 'aed44918'],\\n    ['8b95d6d1', 'a2e8e7f6'],\\n    ['a4f989c2', 'd011f41b'],\\n    ['add9c322', 'cbe62450'],\\n    ['b977be4a', 'c908edd0'],\\n    ['cd7f1687', 'fcfcc902'],\\n    ['f321a31c', 'fa667be2'],\\n]\\n\\n\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/698449\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-09T23:30:08.615841200Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-10T15:45:31.636666700Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371679Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 699326,\n    \"title\": \"stage.1 : global search using linear prior tvt = linear(md,z)\",\n    \"author\": \"hengck23\",\n    \"author_username\": \"hengck23\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 18,\n    \"comment_count\": 5,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2F1aabc18ee91163e6ba228c5e1db9b147%2FSelection_3505.png?generation=1778687376098048&alt=media)\\n\\nNext post: stage.2 iterative local search for refinement \",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/699326\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-13T15:49:38.319727500Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-06-03T01:37:42.410Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371691Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 698002,\n    \"title\": \"Is online learning / test-time fine-tuning allowed?\",\n    \"author\": \"Kh0a\",\n    \"author_username\": \"llkh0a\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"MASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 17,\n    \"comment_count\": 5,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"With the current evaluation setup, participants can train the model offline and then fine-tune it using the test dataset at submission time by peeking at the actual test dataset. They can only extract the available TVT_input (calibration reference) and other features but can make a solid improvement through domain adaptation.\\n\\nSpecifically, at submission time in a Kaggle notebook:\\n\\n1. Load the hidden test data (wellbores + GR, formation parameters, TVT_input)\\n2. Fine-tune the pre-trained model using test features as input (self-supervised learning using TVT_input as calibration targets)\\n3. Generate final predictions on the adapted model\\n\\nIs this approach considered allowed under the competition rules? Looking forward to feedback from organizers.\\n\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/698002\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-08T04:09:03.521542Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-16T17:55:59.460Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371700Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 701041,\n    \"title\": \"Why naive XGBoost hits a wall here \\u2014 and what the literature suggests instead\",\n    \"author\": \"Nicolas Bridelance\",\n    \"author_username\": \"nbridelancetb\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 17,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"# \\ud83d\\udcda Algorithm Review: Predicting TVT from GR Logs \\u2014 From Signal Processing to Foundation Models\\n\\nI spent a good chunk of time reviewing the literature for this competition before\\nwriting a single line of code. This post is that review, structured as a progressive\\nreading guide \\u2014 from the geological basics to state-of-the-art deep learning.\\n\\nThe philosophy here: understanding *why* an algorithm works on this data is more\\nvaluable than blindly throwing models at it.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. The Physical Problem (Don't Skip This)\\n\\nBefore any algorithm, let's be clear on what we're actually trying to do.\\n\\nWhen a horizontal well is drilled, the drill bit travels *along* geological layers\\nrather than cutting through them vertically. This creates a fundamental ambiguity:\\nat any given MD (Measured Depth \\u2014 the cable length along the borehole), *where\\nexactly are we in the rock pile?*\\n\\nThis is what TVT answers. In this competition specifically, TVT is not a classical\\nlayer thickness \\u2014 it's a **relative geological depth index**: how far vertically\\nare we from a reference surface that follows the local geological structure.\\n\\nThe three depth coordinates:\\n- **MD**: length along the borehole trajectory. The only coordinate tools actually\\n  measure.\\n- **TVD** = $\\\\int_0^{MD} \\\\cos(I)\\\\, dMD$ \\u2014 true vertical depth. Straightforward\\n  geometry.\\n- **TVT**: corrects for both borehole geometry *and* formation dip. This is what\\n  tells you \\\"you're 15 ft above the Buda limestone\\\" regardless of how the well\\n  meanders.\\n\\n### The Gamma Ray as a GPS in the rock\\n\\nGR measures natural radioactivity (K, U, Th) in API units. The key physical fact:\\n\\n- **Shales** concentrate radioactive minerals during deposition \\u2192 **high GR (> 100 API)**\\n- **Carbonates / clean sandstones** are chemically inert \\u2192 **low GR (< 40 API)**\\n\\nThis means each geological formation has a characteristic GR \\\"fingerprint\\\". In the\\nTexas Eagle Ford play targeted here, the stratigraphy reads like a barcode:\\n\\n| Formation | GR character | Role |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Austin Chalk | Low, stable | Roof marker |\\n| Eagle Ford Shale | High, noisy (organic + carbonate interbeds) | The reservoir |\\n| Buda Limestone | Sharp drop | Floor marker |\\n\\nThe **typewell** is a vertical reference well that crossed all these layers in one\\nclean pass. It provides the canonical GR barcode for the area.\\n\\n**The core problem**: the lateral well's GR log is a *deformed version* of this\\nbarcode \\u2014 stretched, compressed, shifted \\u2014 because the well meanders along the\\nlayers rather than cutting through them. Our job is to continuously match the\\ndeformed barcode against the reference to read the stratigraphic position (TVT).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. Dynamic Time Warping \\u2014 The Right Tool for Deformed Signals\\n\\n### Why classic correlation fails first\\n\\nThe naive approach is a simple cross-correlation: slide the lateral GR window over\\nthe typewell GR and find the best match. This works for a **rigid shift** (the same\\nsequence, just offset). But real geology doesn't work that way:\\n\\n- A limestone bed might be 5 ft thick near one well and 12 ft thick 2 km away\\n  (lateral thickness variations due to compaction, paleotopography...)\\n- The drill bit may have spent more time in one layer if the well undulates\\n\\nThe lateral GR signal is **non-linearly stretched** relative to the typewell. Classic\\ncorrelation produces garbage alignments in these cases.\\n\\n### DTW: elastic alignment\\n\\nDTW (Sakoe & Chiba, 1978) \\u2014 originally designed for speech recognition \\u2014 solves\\nexactly this. The insight: instead of finding a single shift, find the optimal\\n*path* through a 2D cost matrix that warps both signals onto each other.\\n\\n$$D(i,j) = c(x_i, y_j) + \\\\min\\\\{D(i-1,j),\\\\; D(i,j-1),\\\\; D(i-1,j-1)\\\\}$$\\n\\nwhere $c(x_i, y_j) = |x_i - y_j|$ is the local cost (GR difference).\\nThe path must start at $(1,1)$ and end at $(N,M)$, cannot go backwards (monotonicity\\nconstraint), and is found in $O(N \\\\times M)$ by dynamic programming.\\n\\n> **Key intuition**: DTW lets one point in the lateral log \\\"match\\\" multiple points\\n> in the typewell (or vice versa). That's the elastic stretching. A thin layer in\\n> the lateral that corresponds to a thick layer in the typewell is handled naturally.\\n\\n### Critical constraints for geology\\n\\nWithout constraints, DTW is prone to degenerate alignments: a single point matching\\nan entire section. Two classical fixes:\\n\\n**Sakoe-Chiba band** \\u2014 only allow alignments within $w$ samples of the diagonal:\\n$$|i - j| \\\\leq w$$\\nThis reduces complexity from $O(N^2)$ to $O(w \\\\cdot N)$ and prevents geologically\\nabsurd matchings (e.g. aligning an 11,000 ft TVT layer with a 9,000 ft layer).\\n\\n**Itakura parallelogram** \\u2014 constrains path slopes to $[1/2, 2]$, forbidding extreme\\ncompression or expansion. Appropriate when the geology is structurally simple and\\nlayer thickness variations are bounded.\\n\\n### Where vanilla DTW breaks down\\n\\n- **Faults / missing rock**: the monotonicity condition ($i_{k-1} \\\\leq i_k$) means\\n  DTW cannot model repeated stratigraphy (reverse faults) or missing sections. You\\n  need external domain knowledge to detect and handle these.\\n- **Error accumulation**: without external anchor points, alignment errors drift in\\n  multi-well correlation loops (the loop doesn't close to zero).\\n- **Open boundary problem**: a lateral well rarely starts at the exact top of the\\n  typewell sequence. Use **Subsequence DTW** (free start/end conditions on one side)\\n  to handle this.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3. Signal Correlation Methods \\u2014 From Rigid to Elastic\\n\\nA useful mental model: think of these three methods as progressively more flexible\\nalignment tools.\\n\\n### 3.1 Classical Cross-Correlation \\u2014 \\\"Does it look the same if I shift it?\\\"\\n\\n$$(f \\\\star g)[\\\\tau] = \\\\sum_t f[t]\\\\, g[t + \\\\tau]$$\\n\\nSlides $g$ over $f$, measures overlap. Fast, simple, but **amplitude-sensitive**:\\ndifferent LWD tools or borehole diameters shift absolute GR values systematically,\\ncreating false alignment peaks. Use only as a very rough first pass.\\n\\n### 3.2 Normalized Cross-Correlation (NCC) \\u2014 \\\"Does it have the same shape?\\\"\\n\\n$$NCC(\\\\tau) = \\\\frac{\\\\sum_t (f[t]-\\\\bar{f})(g[t+\\\\tau]-\\\\bar{g})}\\n{\\\\sqrt{\\\\sum_t(f[t]-\\\\bar{f})^2 \\\\cdot \\\\sum_t(g[t+\\\\tau]-\\\\bar{g})^2}}$$\\n\\nThis is the Pearson correlation coefficient computed on a sliding window. Result is\\nalways in $[-1, 1]$, **completely amplitude-invariant**: if the lateral GR tool reads\\n20% higher than the typewell tool due to borehole conditions, NCC is unaffected.\\n\\n> **Practical rule of thumb**: a sliding NCC score > 0.85 on a 30 m window is a\\n> high-confidence stratigraphic **anchor point**. NCC won't tell you about stretching,\\n> but it tells you \\\"this wiggle in the lateral GR is definitely this wiggle in the\\n> typewell, with high confidence\\\".\\n\\nIn this dataset, we computed NCC scores across 100 wells: the median peak NCC is\\n~0.81, with ~31% of wells showing at least one anchor point above 0.75.\\n\\n### 3.3 Phase Correlation \\u2014 \\\"What's the exact shift, even in noise?\\\"\\n\\n$$\\\\Phi = \\\\mathcal{F}^{-1}\\\\!\\\\left(\\\\frac{F(\\\\omega)\\\\,G^*(\\\\omega)}{|F(\\\\omega)\\\\,G^*(\\\\omega)|}\\\\right)$$\\n\\nOperates entirely in the frequency domain. If $g$ is a shifted copy of $f$, the\\nresult $\\\\Phi$ is a **Dirac impulse** at the exact offset \\u2014 not a smooth correlation\\npeak. This gives sub-sample precision and is robust to broadband noise\\n(LWD tool background noise cancels out during normalization).\\n\\nThe limitation: same as classical cross-correlation, assumes a rigid shift. Best\\nused to detect **coarse offset and faults** at macro scale, before handing off to\\nDTW for local elastic alignment.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. Python Library Benchmark\\n\\n| | `dtaidistance` | `fastdtw` | `tslearn` |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| Backend | C / Cython | Pure Python | Python/Cython |\\n| Complexity | $O(w \\\\cdot N)$ with band | **$O(N)$ approx.** | $O(N \\\\cdot M)$ |\\n| Multivariate | Limited (1D focus) | Yes | Yes (MDTW) |\\n| Special feature | Fastest exact 1D | Coarse-to-fine, linear memory | **Soft-DTW** (differentiable) |\\n| Best for | Production, single-channel | Very long series (> 10k pts) | DL loss functions |\\n\\nThe **Soft-DTW** in `tslearn` deserves a special mention. Standard DTW uses a\\n$\\\\min$ operator which is not differentiable \\u2014 you can't backpropagate through it.\\nSoft-DTW (Cuturi & Blondel, 2017) replaces $\\\\min$ with a smooth approximation\\n$\\\\min_\\\\gamma$, making the alignment loss **trainable end-to-end in a neural network**.\\nThis matters if you want to embed DTW directly in a loss function (e.g. to penalize\\nstratigraphic misalignment in a LSTM or Transformer).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5. Can Foundation Models Help? A Critical Look\\n\\nThe obvious question after reading about DTW and NCC: *\\\"Can we just throw a\\npretrained time series model at this and let it figure it out?\\\"*\\n\\nThe answer is: **maybe, but not the way you'd expect**. Here's why.\\n\\n### What Foundation Models for Time Series actually do\\n\\nOver the past 2 years, several large pretrained models have emerged that work on\\ntime series the same way LLMs work on text: train on billions of diverse sequences,\\nthen zero-shot forecast on new data.\\n\\n**The critical translation for this problem**: our independent variable is\\n**depth (MD)**, not time. We're doing spatial inference along a borehole, not\\ntemporal forecasting. That changes how these models should be used.\\n\\nAlso \\u2014 and this is the key insight \\u2014 **we're not predicting GR**. We're estimating\\na hidden state variable (TVT) from an observed signal (GR) given a reference (typewell).\\nThat's not a forecasting task, it's more like a Bayesian state estimation problem.\\nThis means these models should ideally be used as **feature extractors** (encoder\\nrepresentations \\u2192 regression head), not as direct forecasters.\\n\\n| Model | Architecture | Spatial covariates | High-freq. detail | ROGII fit |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| **TimesFM 2.5** (Google) | Decoder-only (Patch) | \\u2705 XReg | High | **8.5/10** |\\n| **Chronos** (Amazon) | T5 Encoder-Decoder | \\u274c univariate | Medium | 4/10 |\\n| **MOIRAI** (Salesforce) | Masked Encoder | \\u2705 any-variate | High | 7/10 |\\n| **PatchTST** | Encoder-only (Patch) | \\u2705 channel-indep. | Very high | **9/10** |\\n\\n### Why Patching matters for GR logs\\n\\nA single GR measurement at one depth point carries almost no geological information\\non its own \\u2014 it's dominated by tool noise and borehole effects. The geological signal\\nlives in the **shape of the curve over 5\\u201315 ft**: a peak-trough-peak pattern\\nidentifies a formation boundary, a flat plateau identifies a homogeneous rock mass.\\n\\nPatch-based models (PatchTST, TimesFM) encode the input as a sequence of local\\nwindows (\\\"patches\\\") rather than individual points \\u2014 exactly matching the scale at\\nwhich geology expresses itself in a GR log. This is not accidental: it's the right\\ninductive bias for this type of data.\\n\\n### Why Chronos scores low here\\n\\nChronos tokenizes the time series by normalizing and **quantizing** values into a\\ndiscrete vocabulary (like converting a signal into \\\"words\\\"). This works beautifully\\nfor macroscopic trends in economic or climate data.\\n\\nBut in a GR log, a 1 m thin carbonate interlayer \\u2014 a potential key stratigraphic\\nmarker \\u2014 appears as a brief high-amplitude spike. Quantization smooths or misclassifies\\nthis spike, potentially erasing the very feature that pins the stratigraphic\\ncorrelation.\\n\\n### The XReg advantage (TimesFM)\\n\\nThis competition is fundamentally spatial: the same TVT can correspond to very\\ndifferent GR values depending on location (X, Y, Z), lateral thickness variations,\\nand structural dip. Igor Kuvaev (ROGII) confirmed in the forum that XYZ coordinates\\ncarry critical spatial information that GR alone cannot resolve.\\n\\nTimesFM's **XReg** feature allows passing exogenous regressors (X, Y, Z, inclination,\\nsurface depths from nearby wells) alongside the GR sequence as conditioning inputs.\\nThat's exactly the architecture we need.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 6. A Few Things the Forum Made Clear\\n\\nA direct quote from Igor Kuvaev (ROGII organizer) paraphrased:\\n\\n> *\\\"XYZ of lateral wells = true spatial position. The typewell = vertical geological\\n> definition (GR as a function of TVT). Connecting the two is the problem.\\\"*\\n\\nSome practical observations from top participants and organizers:\\n\\n- **Naive tabular XGBoost** on [X, Y, Z, MD, GR] hits a glass ceiling around ~9.7\\n  public LB. It ignores the physical trajectory of the well.\\n- **Geological layers are spatially continuous**. A test well missing surface depth\\n  data can have it imputed from its 10 nearest geographical neighbors with very high\\n  accuracy (R\\u00b2 > 0.99 in cross-validation on the training set).\\n- **Sequential context matters**: the 50 points just before the PS (Prediction Start)\\n  contain the local slope, GR trend, and last known TVT \\u2014 the highest-value features\\n  for immediate prediction.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe problem calls for a layered approach matching each method to what it does best:\\n\\n| Method | Handles stretching | Amplitude-invariant | Best use |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| Classical cross-corr | \\u274c | \\u274c | Initial rough alignment |\\n| NCC (sliding window) | \\u274c | \\u2705 | Anchor point detection |\\n| Phase correlation | \\u274c | \\u2705 | Coarse fault/offset detection |\\n| DTW (Sakoe-Chiba) | \\u2705 | \\u274c | Local elastic alignment |\\n| PatchTST / TimesFM (encoder) | \\u2705 | \\u2705 | Deep feature extraction |\\n\\nHappy to discuss any of this \\u2014 particularly the DTW implementation details\\n(subsequence DTW and open boundaries are tricky to get right). \\ud83d\\ude42\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/701041\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-18T14:47:01.160121600Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-18T14:47:01.160Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371709Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 702131,\n    \"title\": \"A geophysicist's take: domain priors + Q-3D tortuosity (public notebook + repo)\",\n    \"author\": \"Matteo Niccoli\",\n    \"author_username\": \"mycarta\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 16,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"# Kaggle discussion post - ROGII competition\\n\\n---\\n\\nSharing a notebook and a public repo that approach this competition from a geological reasoning angle rather than pure ML optimization.\\n\\n**Notebook:** https://www.kaggle.com/code/mycarta/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction-toolkit\\n\\n**GitHub repo:**  https://github.com/mycarta/rogii-geosteering-toolkit\\n\\nSingle LightGBM, no particle filters or stacking. Mid-pack on the leaderboard, but the findings may be useful to others working on this problem:\\n\\n- **Within-well TVT-Z decoupling.** The global TVT-vs-Z correlation is r = -0.96, but within a single lateral it's essentially zero (mean slope +0.057). The global signal is cross-well structural elevation dominated by build-section geometry. Features based on the global relationship don't work until you account for this.\\n\\n- **Q-3D tortuosity (Jing et al. 2022) was the most useful domain feature** in the ablation (-0.107 RMSE). High tortuosity = active steering = formation deviating from plan.\\n\\n- **Signed drilling azimuth matters.** Opposite directions along the same line see the formation in opposite sequence. The updip/downdip distinction is real and the model uses it via sin/cos azimuth encoding paired with dZ/dMD.\\n\\n- **Well-level AEON features (Catch22 + ClaSP) made the model worse** (+0.476 RMSE). Well-level features under GroupKFold overfit on cross-well noise. Documented as a negative result in the ablation table.\\n\\n- **Considered Verde's BlockKFold for spatial CV, rejected it.** Validation wells are spatially interleaved with training (interpolation, not extrapolation), so spatial blocking is more pessimistic than the actual test condition. Used StratifiedGroupKFold stratified by signed azimuth, median TVT, and spatial location instead.\\n\\nThe notebook includes a cumulative ablation table, Phase 1 spatial recon figures (well center map, azimuth rose, lateral slope distribution), a MASS-equivalent-to-NCC pedagogical demo, and a Q-3D tortuosity visualization.\\n\\nThe GitHub repo has the reusable toolkit modules (wellbore tortuosity from XYZ trajectories, log despiking, sliding distance correlation) and two methodology write-ups on the TVT-Z decoupling finding and the AEON evaluation.\\n\\nFeedback welcome, especially from anyone with geosteering or horizontal drilling experience. What domain features would you add?\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/702131\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-21T13:41:20.677721Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-21T13:41:20.676666700Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371718Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 698282,\n    \"title\": \"Defintion of tvt\",\n    \"author\": \"Moonimonster\",\n    \"author_username\": \"mooncdaiam\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 15,\n    \"comment_count\": 13,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"Hope y'all enjoying this competition!\\n\\nI was wondering what you all defined this 'tvt', the target.\\nIt seams like it means just literal 'depth' as described in typewell.\\nbut I don't really think it is true meaning of tvt.. I searched up on internet, and I found out it means thickness of 'something'., but I'm not really sure what 'something' is in this competition.\\n\\nPretty sure, it would mean something more than 'depth', cause.. what would be the meaning of finding tvt where we have z right? \\nI'm still working on this issue.\\nHope some of you can share ideas about it. Thank you!\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/698282\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-05-09T06:29:46.065751300Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-24T17:59:57.370Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:40.776392+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T07:01:33.371726Z\"\n  },\n  {\n\n---scores file---\n\n---writeups file---\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
