{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_33","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' /tmp/rogii_overview.md\nprintf '\\\\n---dataset---\\\\n'\nsed -n '1,160p' /tmp/rogii_dataset.md\nprintf '\\\\n---summary prior run maybe---\\\\n'\nfind /nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021 -maxdepth 2 -type f | sed -n '1,50p'\nsed -n '1,260p' /nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/brief.md 2>/dev/null || true\"","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_33","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' /tmp/rogii_overview.md\nprintf '\\\\n---dataset---\\\\n'\nsed -n '1,160p' /tmp/rogii_dataset.md\nprintf '\\\\n---summary prior run maybe---\\\\n'\nfind /nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021 -maxdepth 2 -type f | sed -n '1,50p'\nsed -n '1,260p' /nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/brief.md 2>/dev/null || true\"","aggregated_output":"Drilling a horizontal well is like navigating underground without a map. The path forward runs through layers of rock you can’t see.\n\nBuild models to predict the geology along a horizontal wellbore. Your work will help automate and improve drilling operations in the oil and gas industry.\n\na month ago\n\n2 months to go\n\n### Description\n\nRoughly 10,000 horizontal wells are drilled worldwide every year, yet much of the drilling process still relies on manual interpretation by experts. These operations require immense technical precision, where even small deviations from the target zone can lead to significant resource waste. If the well drifts into less favorable geology, it results in inefficient energy recovery and may require additional corrective measures that increase the overall environmental footprint of the site.\n\nInterpreting the subsurface is challenging because direct measurements are inherently limited. Data from wells, seismic surveys, and logging tools only show part of the picture. Rock layers start out stacked like a layer cake, but can bend or break along faults, making it hard to know exactly where the drill bit sits within the formation. Geologists and engineers analyze incoming data to steer the well, but current analytical tools often struggle to match the nuance of expert interpretation.\n\nIn this competition, you’ll develop machine learning models that predict the geology encountered along a horizontal wellbore. Your models should identify favorable layers from drilling data and help guide well placement more accurately during operations.\n\nYour solution could help reduce resource waste by minimizing redundant drilling, improve operational safety by better predicting geological hazards, and move the industry toward automated systems that make faster, more consistent, and data-driven decisions.\n\nA clearer map beneath the surface could make every meter count.\n\n### Evaluation\n\nSubmissions are scored on the root mean squared error. RMSE is defined as:\n\nRMSE\n\n=\n\n1\n\n𝑛\n\n∑\n\n𝑖\n\n=\n\n1\n\n𝑛\n\n(\n\n𝑦\n\n𝑖\n\n−\n\n𝑦\n\n^\n\n𝑖\n\n)\n\n2\n\nwhere\n\n𝑦\n\n^\n\nis the predicted value,\n\n𝑦\n\nis the original value, and\n\n𝑛\n\nis the number of rows in the test data.\n\n### Submission File\n\nFor each row in the test set, you must predict the value of the target tvt as described on the data tab, each on a separate row in the submission file. The file should contain a header and have the following format:\n\nid,tvt\n\n000d7d20_1442,0.0\n\n000d7d20_1443,0.0\n\n000d7d20_1444,0.0\n\n000d7d20_1445,0.0\n\n...\n\n### Timeline\n\nMay 5, 2026 - Start Date.\n\nJuly 29, 2026 - Entry Deadline. You must accept the competition rules before this date in order to compete.\n\nJuly 29, 2026 - Team Merger Deadline. This is the last day participants may join or merge teams.\n\nAugust 5, 2026 - Final Submission Deadline.\n\nAll deadlines are at 11:59 PM UTC on the corresponding day unless otherwise noted. The competition organizers reserve the right to update the contest timeline if they deem it necessary.\n\n### Code Requirements\n\nSubmissions to this competition must be made through Notebooks. In order for the \"Submit\" button to be active after a commit, the following conditions must be met:\n\nCPU Notebook <= 9 hours run-time\n\nGPU Notebook <= 9 hours run-time\n\nInternet access disabled\n\nFreely & publicly available external data is allowed, including pre-trained models\n\nSubmission file must be named submission.csv\n\nPlease see the Code Competition FAQ for more information on how to submit. And review the code debugging doc if you are encountering submission errors.\n\n### Prizes\n\n1st Place - $25,000\n\n2nd Place - $13,000\n\n3rd Place - $7,000\n\n4th Place - $5,000\n\n### Citation\n\n---dataset---\nThe competition data comprises horizontal well trajectories and vertical reference logs (Typewells) used for geological prediction. Your goal is to predict the TVT (True Vertical Thickness) for the evaluation zone of each horizontal well.\n\nThe data is organized into train/ and test/ directories, where each well is identified by a unique 8-character hash (e.g., 015fe0d2).\n\nFile and Field Information\n\ntrain/ Contains the training data. Each well has three associated files:\n\n{WELLNAME}__horizontal_well.csv - Trajectory, geological surfaces, and log data.\n\nWELLNAME - unique identifier for the well.\n\nMD - Measured Depth (ft): The total length of the wellbore from the surface.\n\nX - Easting (ft): Spatial coordinate in the horizontal plane.\n\nY - Northing (ft): Spatial coordinate in the horizontal plane.\n\nZ - True Vertical Depth (ft): The vertical distance below sea level.\n\nANCC, ASTNU, ASTNL, EGFDU, EGFDL, BUDA - Predicted depth of various geological formations (Training only).\n\nTVT - True Vertical Thickness (ft): The manually interpreted geological position for each 1 ft of the lateral well. This is the target variable (Training only).\n\nGR - Gamma Ray (API): Log measuring natural radioactivity of the rock.\n\nTVT_input - Input Target (ft): A copy of TVT provided as a feature. This column contains NaN values for the evaluation zone.\n\n{WELLNAME}__typewell.csv - Vertical reference log for geological correlation.\n\nTVT - Vertical Depth Index (ft): Primary depth reference for the vertical log. Corresponds to TVT (geological position) of the associated horizontal well.\n\nGR - Gamma Ray (API): The vertical Gamma Ray signature used for correlation.\n\nGeology - Formation Label: Categorical label indicating the geological unit (e.g., EGFDL, BUDA).\n\n{WELLNAME}.png - Visualization of the well path and geological cross-section.\n\ntest/ Contains the evaluation data for about 200 wells. Each well has two associated files:\n\n{WELLNAME}__horizontal_well.csv - Trajectory and log data. In these files, the TVT target is hidden (replaced with NaN) in the evaluation zone.\n\n{WELLNAME}__typewell.csv - Vertical reference log for the test well.\n\nNote that the test/ folder visible here contains only a few instances from the training set as example data to help you author your submissions. When your submission is rerun on the hidden test set, these will be replaced with the actual test data.\n\nsample_submission.csv - A sample submission file in the correct format.\n\nid - A unique identifier for each prediction point, formatted as {WELLNAME}_{row_index} (e.g., 015fe0d2_1654).\n\ntvt - Your predicted True Vertical Thickness (ft).\n\n### Files\n\n2327 files\n\nSize\n\n1.33 GB\n\nType\n\ncsv, png, pptx\n\nLicense\n\nSubject to Competition Rules\n\n---summary prior run maybe---\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/brief.md\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/plots/dataset_shape.png\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/plots/score_ladder.png\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/plots/discussion_signals.png\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/plots/discussion_signals.json\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/plots/score_ladder.json\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/plots/dataset_shape.json\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/prompt.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/trace.jsonl\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/discussion_697416.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernel_romantamrazov_rogii-super-solution-lb-top-3.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/leaderboard_writeups.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/top_kernel_scores.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernel_nina2025_rogii-h-blend-v1.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernel_pixiux_rogii-dual-pipeline-blend.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/discussion_ingest_votes.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernel_cdeotte_xgb-starter-cv-15.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/dataset_description.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/discussion_697431.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/discussion_699289.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/discussions_top_votes.json\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernels_top_votes.json\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/discussion_699853.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/competition_overview.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernel_ingest_votes.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernel_hengck23_cnn-mtp-example.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/discussion_697418.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernel_ravaghi_wellbore-geology-prediction-hill-climbing.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernel_pilkwang_rogii-eda-target-free-alignment-for-tvt.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernel_ravaghi_wellbore-geology-prediction-ridge.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/discussion_700424.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/discussion_697406.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/kernel_nihilisticneuralnet_9-251-rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction-dwt-based.txt\n/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_021/raw/discussion_698825.txt\n# ROGII Wellbore Geology Prediction — Strategy Brief\n\n**Competition:** [ROGII - Wellbore Geology Prediction](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction)  \n**Research run:** 2026-06-13 UTC  \n**Goal:** predict hidden-zone `tvt` for horizontal wells from trajectory/log data and each well's vertical typewell reference log.\n\n## Executive Takeaways\n\n- This is mainly a **per-well geosteering / sequence-alignment problem**, not a plain row-wise tabular regression problem. The public notebooks and highest-signal discussions converge on aligning horizontal `GR` against typewell `GR` and preserving `TVT_input` continuity.\n- A credible solution path starts with a **last-known `TVT_input` residual baseline**, adds robust per-well features and GroupKFold validation, then layers in **target-free alignment / DTW / beam search / particle-filter paths**.\n- Strong public work appears to blend several families: physical/formation baselines, signal-alignment outputs, and tabular learners. The most copied ideas are DWT/DTW-style alignment, ridge/SP pipelines, hill climbing/blending, and particle-filter/beam-search features.\n- Public-score retrieval hit Kaggle API 429 during this run, so score claims below are **title-claims unless explicitly marked local CV**. Votes are used only as discovery signal, not as a performance ranking.\n\n## Competition Mechanics That Matter\n\n- **Target:** `tvt`, one prediction for each hidden/evaluation-zone row in `submission.csv` as `id,tvt`.\n- **Metric:** RMSE, so large local misalignments in a well are costly; consistency along a trajectory matters.\n- **Submission environment:** notebook-only, CPU/GPU runtime <= 9 hours, internet disabled, output file must be `submission.csv`.\n- **Data:** each well has a horizontal well CSV and a typewell CSV. Training wells also include PNG visualizations and hidden-zone labels for validation. The visible test folder has only sample instances; hidden rerun test is about 200 wells according to the dataset page.\n- **Local training data shape:** the downloaded data in this workspace has 773 train horizontal wells, 773 train typewells, and 773 PNGs; train horizontal CSVs contain ~5.09M rows, of which ~3.78M rows are evaluation-zone rows where `TVT_input` is missing.\n\n![Local competition data shape](plots/dataset_shape.png)\n\n## Score Ladder From Gathered Evidence\n\nPublic kernel score lookup (`fetch_top_kernel_scores.py`) returned Kaggle API 429, so the ladder separates **verified local CV** from **unverified title-claimed LB values**.\n\n| Rung | RMSE | Evidence | How to read it |\n|---|---:|---|---|\n| Strong naive baseline | ~15.9 | [XGB Starter - CV 15](https://www.kaggle.com/code/cdeotte/xgb-starter-cv-15) | Kernel states the flat last-known-`TVT_input` baseline scored about 15.9 RMSE locally. |\n| Public title-claim | 9.956 | [ROGII Better Solution LB 9.956](https://www.kaggle.com/code/romantamrazov/rogii-better-solution-lb-9-956) | Title contains LB value; not independently verified this run. |\n| Public title-claim | 9.251 | [9.251 DWT-based](https://www.kaggle.com/code/nihilisticneuralnet/9-251-rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction-dwt-based) | Title contains score; not independently verified this run. |\n| Public title-claim | 8.860 | [LB 8.860 sel15 256 seeds](https://www.kaggle.com/code/needless090/lb-8-860-rogii-sel15-256seeds) | Title contains score; not independently verified this run. |\n| Public title-claim | 7.776 | [LB 7.776 ridge SP](https://www.kaggle.com/code/lightningv08/lb-7-776-rogii-ridge-sp) | Title contains score; not independently verified this run. |\n\n![Score ladder](plots/score_ladder.png)\n\n## Key Public Notebooks To Study\n\n### Baselines and Validation\n\n- [XGB Starter - CV 15](https://www.kaggle.com/code/cdeotte/xgb-starter-cv-15) — the cleanest starter for mechanics: GroupKFold by well, residual learning over the last-known `TVT_input`, per-well context features, and simple typewell gamma-ray correlation features.\n- [NN Starter - CV 15.5](https://www.kaggle.com/code/cdeotte/nn-starter-cv-15-5) — useful counterpart for neural sequence/tabular framing, but the XGB starter is the clearer first implementation target.\n- [EDA Starter](https://www.kaggle.com/code/cdeotte/eda-starter) — useful for understanding file layout, well-level segmentation, and what the hidden-zone mask looks like.\n\n### Alignment, Geosteering, and Physical Signals\n\n- [ROGII EDA + Target-Free Alignment for TVT](https://www.kaggle.com/code/pilkwang/rogii-eda-target-free-alignment-for-tvt) — high-signal notebook for the central idea: infer a TVT path by aligning horizontal GR to typewell GR without using hidden targets.\n- [ROGII Target-Free TVT Geosteering](https://www.kaggle.com/code/pilkwang/rogii-target-free-tvt-geosteering) — extends the geosteering framing; study it for target-free inference logic.\n- [ROGII Wellbore TVT — Physical Model](https://www.kaggle.com/code/sunnywu27/rogii-wellbore-tvt-physical-model) — a useful physics-informed baseline family for continuity and trajectory constraints.\n- [Drift Targeting + NCC: Tree-based ROGII Wellbore](https://www.kaggle.com/code/mitchgansemer/drift-targeting-ncc-tree-based-rogii-wellbore) — combines normalized cross-correlation/drift features with tree models.\n- [GR Features / Outlier Detection — ROGII Wellbore](https://www.kaggle.com/code/mitchgansemer/gr-features-outlier-detection-rogii-wellbore) — study for robust GR feature engineering and anomaly handling.\n\n### Strong Public Solution Families\n\n- [9.251 ROGII-Wellbore Geology Prediction: DWT-based](https://www.kaggle.com/code/nihilisticneuralnet/9-251-rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction-dwt-based) — combines GroupKFold, Ridge/CatBoost/LightGBM, formation columns, beams, particle filters, stochastic DTW/DWT-style warping, and typewell GR interpolation. Title claims 9.251.\n- [ROGII SUPER SOLUTION | LB: TOP 3](https://www.kaggle.com/code/romantamrazov/rogii-super-solution-lb-top-3) — advanced blend of LightGBM/CatBoost, seven beam configs, multi-scale NCC, particle filters, formation-surface reliability, monotonic GR trend features, and positive Ridge stacking.\n- [Wellbore Geology Prediction | Ridge](https://www.kaggle.com/code/ravaghi/wellbore-geology-prediction-ridge) — compact ridge/SP-style pipeline; good source for fast local CV and simple blend inputs.\n- [Wellbore Geology Prediction | Hill Climbing](https://www.kaggle.com/code/ravaghi/wellbore-geology-prediction-hill-climbing) — shows how public pipelines are post-processed/blended via hill climbing.\n- [rogii_dual_pipeline_blend](https://www.kaggle.com/code/pixiux/rogii-dual-pipeline-blend) — practical blend notebook; useful once you have two or more diverse prediction families.\n- [ROGII h-blend v1](https://www.kaggle.com/code/nina2025/rogii-h-blend-v1) and [rogii-sp45-fleongg-blend-v2](https://www.kaggle.com/code/jaemin3404/rogii-sp45-fleongg-blend-v2) — public blend references for ensembling many kernels/prediction families.\n\n## Key Discussions and Community Signals\n\nThe most useful discussions are about problem geometry, typewell interpretation, and alignment strategy rather than generic ML tuning.\n\n- [Diagram of the problem](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697418) — high-level conceptual diagram. Comments emphasize that `TVT` behaves like a geology-position coordinate and that direct `MD/Z` reasoning is insufficient.\n- [How Geologists Interpret Wells: Some Helpful Tips](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/698825) — organizer/geologist hints; treat this as domain framing for how human interpreters correlate logs.\n- [besides regression, also dwt (time warping)!](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697431) — early signal that dynamic/time warping is not optional if aiming high.\n- [multi-trajectory prediction (MTP) with deep CNN for welllog inversion](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/699853) — proposes multi-path hypotheses / MDN-style outputs for ambiguous GR alignments; links [cnn-mtp-example](https://www.kaggle.com/code/hengck23/cnn-mtp-example).\n- [Share an UI visualizer](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/700424) — useful for visual error analysis and manual sanity checks of well paths.\n- [Paradigm Shift: Why pure Tabular Models might be hitting a wall](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/699289) — argues for spatial/sequential context over pure row-wise tabular modeling.\n- [Geological Formations on well Geology](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697406) — decodes formation labels (`ANCC`, `ASTNU`, `ASTNL`, `EGFDU`, `EGFDL`, `BUDA`) and helps interpret formation-surface features.\n\n![Discussion signals](plots/discussion_signals.png)\n\n## What It Takes To Do Well\n\n### 1. Build a leak-safe well-level validation loop\n\nUse GroupKFold or well-held-out validation. Rows from the same well are strongly correlated; row-wise random splits will overstate performance. The [XGB Starter - CV 15](https://www.kaggle.com/code/cdeotte/xgb-starter-cv-15) is the reference implementation style: train on hidden-zone rows in training wells, group by well, and evaluate RMSE on held-out wells.\n\n### 2. Treat `TVT_input` as the anchor, not just another feature\n\nThe last known `TVT_input` before the hidden zone is a powerful continuity anchor. A flat continuation is already a ~15.9 local-CV baseline in [XGB Starter - CV 15](https://www.kaggle.com/code/cdeotte/xgb-starter-cv-15). Stronger approaches predict a residual/path continuation from that anchor rather than predicting absolute `TVT` independently.\n\n### 3. Align horizontal GR to typewell GR\n\nThe task-specific signal is the match between the horizontal well’s `GR` sequence and the typewell’s `GR` indexed by `TVT`. Public work repeatedly uses target-free alignment, DTW/DWT, normalized cross-correlation, beam search, and particle filtering: see [Target-Free Alignment for TVT](https://www.kaggle.com/code/pilkwang/rogii-eda-target-free-alignment-for-tvt), [DWT-based 9.251](https://www.kaggle.com/code/nihilisticneuralnet/9-251-rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction-dwt-based), and [SUPER SOLUTION](https://www.kaggle.com/code/romantamrazov/rogii-super-solution-lb-top-3).\n\n### 4. Generate multiple plausible TVT paths\n\nAmbiguity is intrinsic: repeated GR motifs can align to multiple typewell intervals. The MTP discussion and [cnn-mtp-example](https://www.kaggle.com/code/hengck23/cnn-mtp-example) frame this as multi-trajectory prediction; top public notebooks operationalize similar diversity with many beam configurations, particle-filter seeds, and ensemble scales.\n\n### 5. Feed alignment outputs into tabular learners\n\nTree models still help once given the right path features. Strong notebooks combine alignment-derived candidates (`beam`, `NCC`, particle-filter paths, formation offsets, `tw_diff` families) with LightGBM/CatBoost/Ridge stacks. Study [SUPER SOLUTION](https://www.kaggle.com/code/romantamrazov/rogii-super-solution-lb-top-3), [Ridge](https://www.kaggle.com/code/ravaghi/wellbore-geology-prediction-ridge), and [Drift Targeting + NCC](https://www.kaggle.com/code/mitchgansemer/drift-targeting-ncc-tree-based-rogii-wellbore).\n\n### 6. Blend diverse families, then constrain the path\n\nBlend families that make different errors: flat/slope baselines, formation-surface baselines, GR-alignment paths, and tree-model residuals. Use local GroupKFold OOF predictions for weights, then test hill-climbing/ridge stacking as in [Hill Climbing](https://www.kaggle.com/code/ravaghi/wellbore-geology-prediction-hill-climbing), [dual_pipeline_blend](https://www.kaggle.com/code/pixiux/rogii-dual-pipeline-blend), and [h-blend v1](https://www.kaggle.com/code/nina2025/rogii-h-blend-v1). Apply continuity/smoothness checks because physically implausible jumps often indicate a bad alignment.\n\n## Recommended Implementation Plan\n\n1. **Reproduce starter CV:** run a well-grouped residual baseline from [XGB Starter - CV 15](https://www.kaggle.com/code/cdeotte/xgb-starter-cv-15); confirm flat baseline and model CV on held-out wells.\n2. **Add path baselines:** implement last-known, recent-slope, Z/MD slope, formation-surface offsets, and typewell interpolation candidates.\n3. **Implement alignment features:** start with local normalized cross-correlation windows, then add DTW/DWT or beam-search paths following [Target-Free Alignment](https://www.kaggle.com/code/pilkwang/rogii-eda-target-free-alignment-for-tvt) and [DWT-based](https://www.kaggle.com/code/nihilisticneuralnet/9-251-rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction-dwt-based).\n4. **Create diverse candidate trajectories:** vary window sizes, smoothing, beam move costs, particle-filter seeds, and anchor assumptions; store every candidate as per-row and per-well features.\n5. **Train residual learners:** LightGBM/CatBoost/Ridge on OOF features, grouped by well; inspect error by well length, GR quality, and formation interval.\n6. **Blend and post-process:** positive Ridge or hill-climbing on OOF predictions; enforce monotonic/continuity constraints where they improve CV; visualize worst wells with the UI/plotting ideas from [Share an UI visualizer](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/700424).\n7. **Prepare notebook submission:** keep the final pipeline deterministic, no internet, <=9 hours; cache only allowed public inputs; write `submission.csv` exactly.\n\n## Risks and Checks\n\n- **Public notebook scores are volatile and unverified here.** Because the score helper hit 429, treat title scores as directional only.\n- **Public test folder is not representative.** It contains sample cases from training; the hidden rerun has the real evaluation wells.\n- **Validation can lie if grouped incorrectly.** Never let rows from the same well appear in both train and validation folds.\n- **Pure tabular models plateau.** The discussions and strong kernels suggest row-wise regression without alignment misses the core geologic correlation problem.\n- **Over-blending public kernels can overfit the public LB.** Prefer OOF-based weights and inspect per-well residuals.\n\n## Research Artifacts\n\n- Raw gathered evidence is under `raw/` in this run directory.\n- Plot PNGs and provenance JSON sidecars are under `plots/`.\n- Plot sidecars: `plots/score_ladder.json`, `plots/discussion_signals.json`, `plots/dataset_shape.json`.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
